===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|obsolete|outside|heraldry|lang=en}} A [[step]] on a set of [[stairs]]; the [[rung]] of a ladder. {{defdate|from 13th c.}}
# An individual step, or stage, in any process or scale of values. {{defdate|from 13th c.}}
# A stage of [[rank]] or privilege; social standing. {{defdate|from 13th c.}}
#* '''1526''', {{w|William Tyndale}}, trans. ''Bible'', Luke XX:
#*: Master, we knowe that thou sayest, and teachest ryght, nether considerest thou eny mannes '''degre''', but techest the waye of god truely.
# {{context|genealogy|lang=en}} A ‘step’ in genealogical [[descent]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#* '''2002''', {{w|Colin Jones (historian)|Colin Jones}}, ''The Great Nation'', Penguin 2003, page 140:
#*: Louis created the École militaire in Paris in 1751, in which 500 scholarships were designated for noblemen able to prove four '''degrees''' of noble status.
# {{context|now|_|rare|lang=en}} One's relative state or experience; [[way]], [[manner]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#* '''1851''', {{w|Herman Melville}}, ''{{w|Moby-Dick}}'':
#*: If they but knew it, almost all men in their '''degree''', some time or other, cherish very nearly the same feelings towards the ocean with me.
# The amount that an entity possesses a certain property; relative [[intensity]], [[extent]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1898|author={{w|Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill}}
|title={{w|The Celebrity}}|chapter=1
|passage=In the old days, to my commonplace and unobserving mind, he gave no evidences of genius whatsoever. He never read me any of his manuscripts,&nbsp;[&hellip;], and therefore my lack of detection of his promise may in some '''degree''' be pardoned.}}
#: {{usex|To what '''degree''' do the two accounts of the accident concur?|lang=en}}
# A stage of proficiency or qualification in a course of study, now especially an [[award]] bestowed by a [[university]] or, in some countries, a [[college]], as a certification of [[academic]] [[achievement]]. (In the United States, can include secondary schools.) {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#: {{usex|She has two bachelor's '''degrees''' and is studying towards a master's '''degree'''.|lang=en}}
# {{context|geometry|lang=en}} A unit of [[measurement]] of [[angle]] equal to 1/360 of a [[circle]]'s circumference. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
#: {{usex|A right angle is a ninety '''degree''' angle.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|Most humans have a field of vision of almost 180 '''degrees'''.|lang=en}}
# {{context|physics|lang=en}} A unit of measurement of [[temperature]] on any of several [[scales]], such as [[Celsius]] or [[Fahrenheit]]. {{defdate|from 18th c.}}
#: {{usex|90 '''degrees''' Fahrenheit is equivalent to 32.2 '''degrees''' Celsius.|lang=en}}
#: {{usex|Water boils at 100 '''degrees''' Celsius.|lang=en}}
# {{context|mathematics|lang=en}} The sum of the [[exponent]]s of a [[term]]; the [[order]] of a [[polynomial]]. {{defdate|from 18th c.}}
# {{context|graph theory|lang=en}} The number of [[edge]]s that a [[vertex]] takes part in; a [[valency]].
# {{context|surveying|lang=en}} The [[curvature]] of a circular arc, expressed as the angle [[subtend]]ed by a fixed length of arc or chord.

